body_text.text:
Many iris pillars with broad bases pass from the iris root and taper to a fine insertion into the termination of Descemet's
membrane and the surrounding sclerocorneal stroma. The broad insertions provide a firm anchorage for the long thin iris and large ciliary process attached to its rear surface, which in turn suspend a comparatively large lens. The pillars are approximately 0.1 to 0.2 mm apart and lead to a prominent ciliary cleft. The trabecular meshwork of the rabbit is relatively rudimentary (Fig. 2
).
